<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="261" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[813,1455,1674,1778]" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">
ETYMOLOGY. — The species name is an adjective derived from 
<collectingCountry name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">Saint Helena</collectingCountry>
island, and as in some other similar names, the last vowel in the proper name is suppressed, and the suffix - 
<emphasis box="[1298,1340,1728,1751]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">ensis</emphasis>
is added to indicate its current distribution.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="261" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="36.[813,1455,1799,1850]" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">
DISTRIBUTION. — Only known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1165,1286,1800,1824]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">Saint Helena</collectingCountry>
island, in subtidal rocky bottoms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="261" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="36.[813,1456,1872,2029]" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">
DIAGNOSIS. — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Savigny in Lamarck" authorityYear="1818" box="[965,1038,1873,1896]" class="Polychaeta" family="Hesionidae" genus="Hesione" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="36" pageNumber="261" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[965,1038,1873,1896]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="261">Hesione</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with prostomium slightly curved laterally; parapodia with dorsal cirri basally swollen, dorsal cirrophore twice as long as wide; larger acicula blackish; acicular lobe single, short, massive, blunt, upper tine 3 times longer than lower one; neurochaetal blades bidentate, 4-6 times as long as wide; subdistal tooth smaller; guards approaching distal tooth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
